======================================================================
ANALYSIS 11: DOUBLE-DELETION REGULARITY
======================================================================

In standard simplicial homology, d²=0 because deleting pos i then j
pairs with deleting pos j then i-1 (or i then j+1), and signs cancel.
In TRH, this fails when one deletion produces a non-regular path.

Checking: for PASSING tournaments, are ALL double-deletions regular?

  d²=0 AND all faces regular: 240
  d²=0 BUT some face non-regular: 544
  d²≠0 AND some face non-regular: 240
  d²≠0 BUT all faces regular: 0

  → d²=0 does NOT require all faces regular (544 counterexamples)
  → d²=0 can hold even when ∂ maps to paths outside the chain group
     (meaning some terms are 'projected out' but the remaining ones still cancel)

