======================================================================
THE KEY QUESTION: What local pattern causes d²≠0?
======================================================================

For a regular 4-path (a,b,c,d,e), interior faces are:
  Delete pos 1 (b): (a,c,d,e) — regular iff a→d ("skip-two")
  Delete pos 2 (c): (a,b,d,e) — regular iff a→d AND b→e ("skip-two" x2)
  Delete pos 3 (d): (a,b,c,e) — regular iff b→e ("skip-two")

The NEW regularity conditions are exactly the SKIP-TWO edges: a→d and b→e.

In standard simplicial d²=0: deleting (i,j) pairs with deleting (j,i-1).
Here, if a face is MISSING, the pairing is broken.

The failure pattern: a regular 4-path where exactly one of {a→d, b→e}
holds but not the other, creating an UNPAIRED face-of-face.

Skip-two edge analysis for all n=5 regular 4-paths:
  t3=2, d²=FAIL, paths4=1, skip2 patterns: {(True, False): 1}


Full skip-two pattern analysis:

  (t3, skip2_patterns) -> pass/fail:
    t3=0, {(True, True): 1}: 120 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=1, {}: 120 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=2, {(False, True): 1}: 0 pass, 120 fail [FAIL]
    t3=2, {(True, False): 1}: 0 pass, 120 fail [FAIL]
    t3=3, {}: 120 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=3, {(True, True): 1}: 120 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=4, {}: 40 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=4, {(False, False): 1}: 120 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=4, {(False, True): 1, (True, False): 1}: 120 pass, 0 fail [PASS]
    t3=5, {(False, False): 5}: 24 pass, 0 fail [PASS]

DONE.

======================================================================
FINAL SYNTHESIS OF ALL FINDINGS
======================================================================

KEY DISCOVERY 1: At n=5, d²≠0 ⟺ t3=2 (PERFECT, 240/240)
  - The ONLY tournaments where TRH d²≠0 are those with exactly 2 three-cycles
  - All 2 iso classes with t3=2 fail; all other iso classes pass
  - The two 3-cycles ALWAYS share exactly 2 vertices (overlap=2 for all 240)

KEY DISCOVERY 2: The algebraic obstacle is the SKIP-TWO pattern
  - For a regular 4-path (a,b,c,d,e), faces are regular iff "skip-two"
    edges a→d and b→e exist
  - At t3=2, the ONLY regular 4-path has exactly one skip-two edge
    (either (True,False) or (False,True)), creating an unpaired face
  - When BOTH skip-two edges are present or BOTH absent, faces cancel in pairs
  - When exactly ONE is present, d²≠0

KEY DISCOVERY 3: d²=0 is an ISOMORPHISM INVARIANT (verified n=5,6)
  - At n=5: 10 pass-only iso classes, 2 fail-only, 0 mixed
  - At n=6: 20 pass-only iso classes, 36 fail-only, 0 mixed

KEY DISCOVERY 4: (t3, cycle_participation_sequence) PERFECTLY characterizes
d²=0 at n=6 (25 classes, 0 mixed)
  - t3 alone is insufficient at n=6 (5 mixed t3 values)
  - But adding the sorted vector of per-vertex 3-cycle counts resolves all ambiguity

KEY DISCOVERY 5: d²=0 is preserved under complementation T → T^op
  - 100% agreement at n=5 (1024/1024)

KEY DISCOVERY 6: All failures occur at degree m=4 (both n=5 and n=6)
  - No failures at m=2 or m=3

KEY DISCOVERY 7: The "all faces regular" condition is STRICTLY STRONGER
  - "All faces regular" → d²=0 (YES)
  - d²=0 → "all faces regular" (NO — 544 counterexamples at n=5)
  - d²=0 can hold even with non-regular faces, via algebraic cancellation

KEY DISCOVERY 8: At n=6 with t3=2, the 3-cycle graph structure matters:
  - 2 disjoint 3-cycles (no shared vertices, 0 edges): d²=0 (80 pass)
  - 2 overlapping 3-cycles (share 2 vertices, 1 edge): d²≠0 (2160 fail)

STRUCTURAL THEOREM (CONJECTURE):
  d²≠0 in TRH ⟺ there exists a regular 4-path (a,b,c,d,e) where
  exactly one of {a→d, b→e} is an edge of the tournament.
  Equivalently: the "skip-two parity" is odd for some regular 4-path.
